primer.<br>
1. The simplest form of a nuclear reactor is an atomic pile<br>
made of natural Uranium metal.<br>
2. It takes 7150 kilograms of natural uranium to make one<br>
critical mass of it. <br>
3.This should be increased to at least 10-20  critical masses<br>
to make a large Plutonium 239 production reactor.<br>
3. For 10 critical masses 71,500 kg of naturala uranium is needed as fuel.<br>
4. The natural uranium reactor can not be modereated by light water. <br>
5. It must use Heavy water,or graphite as its moderator.<br>
6. The most practical approach is to mix about 72000 kg<br>
of Natural Uranium with About 72000 kg of graphite for 10<br>
critical masses et el.<br>
7. Heavy water is D2O. Graphite is made of pure carbon.<br>
8. The reactor should have a primary,and a secondary coolant loop.<br>
9.The reactor should be placed near a fresh water, lake,inland<br>
sea,or river.<br>
10.All the pieces of Uranium in the pile should be within no more then 30 cm from each other. This is 11.81 inches.<br>
11. Holes should be drilled verticaly all the way through this pile .<br>
12. Boron or cadmium neutron absorbing control  rodes will be inserted into all these holes. Natural Uranium metal rods<br>
will also be onserted through these holes.<br>
13. This reactor should placed in a swimming pool made <br>
steel or concrete and filled with lite water H2O.<br>
14. If D20 is used it will serve as both coolant and moderater.<br>
15. If D2O is used the swimming pool will be filled with D20.<br>
16. The control rods, and the Uranium rods  will be inserted from  a steel catwallk above the swimming pool. The rods will all be operated by electric motors.After the Uranium rods have had a significant fraction of their mass converted into Pu-239 they will be removed dissolved in HFL ,and processed<br>
to extract the Plutonium metal  from them as  is done with<br>
 Uranium metal during the enrichment process described <br>
previosly by me else where.<br>
17. This swimming pool reactor will be 100% enclosed in a steel or concrete containment vessel.<br>
18. The coolant steam in the primary loop will circulate in the core boil off into a cooling tower,cool, recondense back into water, and rain back into the core through other pipes. <br>
19. There will be a pipe that will collect the steam  it rises from the core .<br>
21.  There will be a heat exchanger pipe in contact with this pipe,that will carrry the water of the secondary loop,pass its steam through turbines, and release it after it is used.<br>
